        "<p>Bennet, with little cessation, of his house and garden at Hunsford. Such</p>\n<p>doings discomposed Mr. Bennet exceedingly. In his library he had been</p>\n<p>always sure of leisure and tranquillity; and though prepared, as he told</p>\n<p>Elizabeth, to meet with folly and conceit in every other room in the</p>\n<p>house, he was used to be free from them there: his civility, therefore,</p>\n<p>was most prompt in inviting Mr. Collins to join his daughters in their</p>\n<p>walk; and Mr. Collins, being in fact much better fitted for a walker</p>",
